  "prompt": "How much of Google's mobile revenue comes from apps versus mobile search in browsers and the mobile web?",
  "response": "As of my latest available data, detailed revenue breakdowns between Google's different mobile revenue streams, such as apps versus mobile search in browsers and the mobile web, are typically not provided in publicly available financial reports. Google generally reports revenues as broader categories such as \u201cGoogle Search & Other,\u201d \u201cYouTube ads,\u201d and \u201cGoogle Network Members' properties.\u201d \n\nHowever, it is widely recognized that mobile search ads represent a significant portion of Google's mobile revenue, as search advertising continues to be one of Google's most profitable segments. Additionally, the Google Play store and mobile apps contribute to Google's revenue via in-app purchases and app downloads.\n\nFor precise figures, you would need to refer to specific disclosures from Google's financial statements or analyst reports specializing in Google's revenue segmentation, but those detailed breakdowns are often proprietary and not publicly shared in detail.",
